result.execSummary:
The defendant Kyle Robert Binter was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possess Drug Paraphernalia, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.573(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Kyle Robert Binter in court with attorney Michael B Plaisted.  Brad Alan Vorpahl appeared for the State of Wisconsin.   Deputy court clerk: LMS.

The defendant has complied with the Deferred Prosecution Agreement.
On motion of the state, the court amended the charge to Possess Drug Paraphernalia, contrary to Wisconsin Statutes section(s) 961.573(1), a class U misdemeanor.   Court ordered entry of judgment of conviction to the amended charge.

Court sentenced defendant to serve 1 DAY in the House of Correction CONSECUTIVE to any sentence with credit for 1 day served; TIME SERVED DISPOSITION.

Court orders defendant to pay all cost, fees and surcharges, including DNA surcharge by 9/10/2015 or a civil judgment to be entered with tax intercept.  Bail on deposit to be applied if applicable.

Court does not suspend driving privileges.

Defendant Kyle Robert Binter in court with attorney Russell Dennis Bohach.  Paul Hauer for Patricia I. Daugherty appeared for the State of Wisconsin. 
Filed, signed Deferred Prosecution Agreement.  The court reviewed the Agreement with the defendant.  
The defendant was advised of his constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum to Plea Questionnaire and Waiver of Rights received and filed.  The parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  The Court found the defendant guilty but WITHHELD entry of Judgment of Conviction for a period of 6 months.
The court approved the Deferred Prosecution Agreement and found it to be in the best interest of the parties and the general public.
Case is adjourned for Review Hearing on 10/28/2014 at 8:30 a.m., Br. 6.  Review hearing scheduled for October 28, 2014 at 08:30 am.
